You can learn more about what CVS is doing in my stories and get your own Sans Retouching t-shirt (featuring the Beauty Mark) at CVS.com! 100% of the proceeds go to @girlsinc #ad

Growth only occurs in the state of discomfort.

I can do small talk alright, but I always crave deeper introspective conversations.  I love discussing those latent issues that people tend to avoid or epiphanies that you only learn through struggles. However a lot of people can’t immediately chat about these things because of their walls or the fear of judgment. 
I find this opening up process quite similar to what an esthetician does. During the facial, you lie down, get your face steamed, washed, exfoliated and then go in with the extractions. The same thing goes for a person and their feelings. You sit down, have a refreshment, talk about light topics, gain their trust and then slowly dive deeper to see their true soul. Wishing that everyone has a fulfilling conversation today. ♥️

#ad Public speaking used to make my stomach churn. Actually it still kinda does, but I have a few tips on calming me down when I'm on stage. Dress in an outfit you feel amazing in, starting with a comfortable base layer, like my @hanes bra and underwear. It's crazy what a killer comfy outfit can do to your confidence. Last year I did four panels and before I went on stage, I looked at my outfit in the mirror and told myself that I'm worth being heard. It's okay to take a pause and gather your thoughts. Time goes a lot slower in your head, especially when you're panicking. The audience can wait so take your time. Find a loved one in the audience and make eye contact. My friends will give me a smile or a funny face and I instantly feel better. #BeComfydent

Like many girls I’ve struggled with body image. I was always on the fuller side growing up and was constantly on the quest to lose weight with crash diets and unattainable health goals. Then in college, the pounds flew off and even though I was at my “goal” weight I was still unhappy. I would get unsolicited comments on how flat and non existent my chest was. It was ridiculous. Another “problem” to fix? When will people stop projecting their unrealistic standards of beauty on everyone and stop this body shaming? We come in all different shapes and sizes and it’s a beautiful thing. When I meet someone, I'm not looking at their body. I care about their soul and character. Embrace your differences and stop the judgement. 
Love, your local representative of the 34A Club ♥️

I’ve always been sensitive and for most of my life I despised the fact that I constantly felt so much. Easy to laugh and easy to crumble. Emotions are seen as weakness, but we need to change this perspective. It is a gift to feel. If you ever feel frustrated for feeling too much, see this as an ability to be in tune with all the energy around you. 
Whenever something makes me feel down or negative energy creeps in I remember this passage by Don Miguel Ruiz, "Whatever happens around you, don’t take it personally. Nothing other people do is because of you. It is because of themselves. Even when a situation seems so personal, even if others insult you directly, it has nothing to do with you. What they say, what they do, and the opinions they give are according to the agreements they have in their own minds.”
